    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-15T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-15T04:00:00-05:00" n="518"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.5/5–1554: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-15T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 15, 1954—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 70. Limit distribution. I took occasion
                    to tell <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> last night that we should
                    be under no illusions about troop withdrawal in Indochina, that it would be very
                    difficult to prevent any lines fixed from developing into <hi rend="italic">de
                        facto</hi> partition which was something US could not accept. If we saw
                    things heading that way, we would have to disassociate ourselves from this
                    particular proposal.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName> replied that would be very
                    serious. He said that military regrouping would postpone any political
                    settlement and that neither Vietnamese nor Viet Minh would accept partition. He
                    realized that if there were any clean-cut split on a given parallel, it would
                    inevitably become partition and for that reason he felt jumbled and irregular
                    lines like frontiers of Israel far safer. I said I agreed with this line of
                    thought.</p>
                <p>I also told him that we were making progress with British and I felt much more
                    optimistic than two weeks ago. I also said we could do a great deal for the long
                    pull, including training, provided it was not necessary for us to intervene
                    directly in present fighting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
